        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0606.jpg" n="part4_p132.jpg" xml:id="img_0132" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p132.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_132_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_2" n="N001"/>[601]
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_3" n="N002"/>dimension of <rs type="keyword" ref="#Ultimacy">ultimacy</rs>. It loses the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Substance">substance </rs>of <ultimate_concern>ultimate concern</ultimate_concern> step by step, becomes shallow and
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_4" n="N003"/>empty, and then becomes desperate about itself. This is the moment where new heteronomies
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_5" n="N004"/>enter into the vacuum, as for instance in the modern time, the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Totalitarian">totalitarian</rs> heteronomies coming from
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_6" n="N005"/>the <rs type="keyword" ref="#State">states</rs>; or being represented still by the churches in their authoritarian or <rs type="keyword" ref="#Fundamentalism">fundamentalistic</rs> ways
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_7" n="N006"/>of thought.
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_8" n="N007"/>Now if this is so, then nothing is more urgent than the question: is there something beyond
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_9" n="N008"/>the alternative of a repressive <rs type="keyword" ref="#Heteronomy">heteronomy</rs> and an emptying <rs type="keyword" ref="#Autonomy">autonomy</rs>? To this fundamental question,
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_10" n="N009"/>l answer: Yes, there is something; let's give it the name ''theonomy''--it is not a quite adequate name,
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_11" n="N010"/>but it is so well related to ''heteronomy'' and ''autonomy'' that one might use it. But then one
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_12" n="N011"/>must define it. It is not a divine law represented by the <church>Church</church> and put upon the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Culture">culture</rs>--that would
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_13" n="N012"/>be heteronomy. <rs type="keyword" ref="#Theonomy">THEOnomy</rs> is autonomy, but aware of its depth-dimension; is autonomy moving on the
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_14" n="N013"/>basis of an <ultimate_concern>ultimate concern</ultimate_concern>. Now the question of course is: how far is this possible? Is it possible at all?
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_15" n="N014"/>It IS possible, if we look at human <rs type="keyword" ref="#History">history</rs>. It is never completely actualized. There is always the one or
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_16" n="N015"/>the other predominant, either the autonomous element or the heteronomy element. In any case,
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_17" n="N016"/>we have periods of history in which the forms of life, the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Art">artistic </rs>forms, the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Cognitive">cognitive</rs> forms, the
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_18" n="N017"/><rs type="keyword" ref="#Politics">political</rs> forms, expressed ultimate concern, with or against the churches. And such periods, as for
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_19" n="N018"/>instance the archaic-Greek <rs type="keyword" ref="#Philosophy">philosophical</rs> period, or the 11th or 12th centuries in the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Middle_Ages">Middle Ages</rs>,
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_20" n="N019"/>or the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Reformation">Reformation</rs> period--such periods are, in some way, theonomous. They do not separate the
               <lb facs="#facs_132_tr_2_tl_21" n="N020"/>ultimate concern and the preliminary concerns. They see, in their preliminary concerns, in the
            </p>
            
